about: Just a few blocks from Columbia University, this quaint coffee shop flaunts beautiful interior design with monstera plants, sun-drenched seating, and  some of the best cappuccino you’ll ever have! Jazz music and chatter fill the background noise, but it’s mellow enough where you get some serious work done.
miniblurb: sun-drenched, plant-filled hip spot with other work-from-homers
insidertips: Sit at the rightmost corner of the bar facing out to the street; there’s a handy outlet that the other bar seats don’t offer. To your right are some gorgeous wall plants and in front is a view of Broadway – great for people-watching!

address: 450 Park Ave S, New York, NY 10016
about: Stepping into this coffee shop in Nomad, you'll likely wonder if this is a coffee shop or a late 19th-century art exhibition. From the hand-drawn murals on the wall (apparently made up of 500 individual tiles) to the iconic terrazzo floor to the soaring dome ceiing and the oil-paint portraits with their orante frames, each detail will make you gawk. The Hickory Smoked S'mores Latte is the ultimate coffee experience that is presented with steaming smoke.
miniblurb: upscale coffee shop with designer decor and innovative drinks
insidertips: Seating available in both the front and back of the store. Outlets underneath most seats. Avoid the seating near the door, as cold wind frequently blows in.

name: Hungarian Pastry Shop
about: Hungarian Pastry Shop, opened in 1961, offers the old-world charm of a classic European cafe with mellow, dim lighting and a display case filled with delicious pastries. This is a popular spot for locals and tourists both to enjoy cup of coffee while soaking in the atmosphere. You'll find a spectrum of scholars here -- students from Barnard and Columbia (just a few blocks away), elderly people flipping through newspapers or discussing niche literature you've likely never heard of.
miniblurb: Mellow coffee and pastries shop with long-standing history
insidertips: Get here early! Seats fill up astronomically quickly. Also, this isn't the best place to whip out all your techy gadgets; there's no Wifi or outlets here, and a quick glance around will affirm to you that many students are huddled over books and papers. I love it here!
image1alt: Interior of Hungarian Pastry Shop, warm and golden, with display shelf of pastries.
image2alt: Close up of array of pastries in display shelf, like oversized cream puffs and chocolate cake slices.
image3alt: People studying in the Coffee Shop with framed collages of books on the wall.
image4alt: Exterior of Hungarian Pastry Shop, with people sitting with their dogs or chatting with friends.

name: Lê Phin
about: Snug and brightly-lit Vietnamese café featuring Asian-inspired flavors and drinks like pandan latte, classic Phin coffee, and sesame and pumpkin sweet potato latte. Space is limited, but if you're able to snag the window-side seating, you're in for a treat! (No restrooms here).
miniblurb: Snug and brightly-lit Vietnamese café with Asian-American flavored drinks.
insidertips: When we say 'cozy', we mean it -- this cafe is tiny! If you're lucky enough, you'll be able to snag the window counter seat looking out onto the street with sunshine streaming through, but when I went, I shared a table with another party.
image1alt: Interior of Lê Phin: white flowers on a wooden table with yellow pillow cushions, with view onto street
image2alt: Man in green sweater sitting at a table next to window-sill seating.
image4alt: Cashier area with pastry display and shelf with trinkets for sale.

name: Interlude Coffee & Tea
about: Marked by minimalist and modern design and pops of muted greenery, Interlude Cafe is a Korean-American owned coffee shop that offers a moment of quiet and calmness in hectic New Yorkers' days. Try the toasted sesame rice crispy and the flash brew.
miniblurb: Minimalist and modern Korean-American-owned cafe with sleek decor
insidertips: This is a small and quiet space; be mindful of others.

name: Remi43 Flower & Coffee
about: A hybrid flower and coffee shop all in one, Remi43 is a well-known spot in Midtown East with stunning latte art. However, the only problem is that the rest of New York also knows it. For that reason, it's worth checking out, but the hustle and bustle and small, cramped tables may not be the best fit for a deep work session. That being said, try the famous rose or lavender latte! I loved it here, but it was too busy.
miniblurb: Coffee shop known for rose latte overflowing with plants and flowers.
insidertips: There are two seating areas: one upstairs and one downstairs. Upstairs, there are outlets, but Wifi is spotty. Downstairs, Wifi is better but lack outlets. Pick your poison...
image1alt: Interior of Remi43 with plants and flowers of all sizes.
image2alt: One cup of rose latte with pink latte art and one blue cup of lavender latte next to a display of succulents.
image3alt: Interior of Remi43 with overflowing wall plants and table plants.
image4alt: Close up of two green matcha lattes, a croissant with golden and green stripes.

name: The Company Clock Coffee Shop
address: Inside the Lobby, 335 Madison Ave, New York, NY 10017
about: Nestled on the first floor of 22 Vanderbilt, Clock Coffee is a coworking space frequented by employees in the corporate building but open to all. Plush green seats in the lobby, reliable Wifi, and high-vaulted, open-air ceilings - what more could you need? I love it here!
miniblurb: Corporate coworking space with plush green seating and solid drinks and amenities.
insidertips: Although Clock Coffee is part of a corporate building and commonly used by employees, anyone can use the space! There are often events that happen here as well, like intimate readings and book signings by authors.
image1alt: Interior of Clock Coffee Shop: plush pink seats, high-vaulted ceilings, and fern plants.
image2alt: Clock Coffee Shop: circular marble tables with black wire chairs and plush green sofas.
image3alt: White, sleek coffee bar of Clock Coffee Shop
image4alt: Close up of the coffee bar of Clock Coffee Shop, with baristas talking in the back.

name: Devoción
about: Consistently amazing coffee thanks to hand-picked beans from Colombia that are shipped within 10 days and roasted right in house. Ambience is beautiful with skylights, leather couches, and an abundant plant wall.
miniblurb: Carefully sourced Colombian coffee served in a light-filled, brick-lined space with leather sofas.
insidertips: There is often a 20+ minute wait to get coffee, so if you're committed to working here, show up early to snag a table!
image1alt: Interior of Devoción: skylight, leather couches, and wooden tables and chairs around the perimeter.
image2alt: Devoción filled with people: individuals chatting, people working on laptops.
image3alt: Interior of Devoción: dark mahogony walls and plants hanging from ceiling.
image4alt: Devoción iced coffee in a plastic cup.

name: The Chipped Cup
about: A cozy coffee shop with a living room to hunker down and write your next screenplay or end-of-semester thesis and to connect with friends and neighbors.
miniblurb: A Victorian psychedelic coffee shop with a touch of grandma’s attic, wabi-sabi, and political sass.
insidertips: This place has a nice, cozy basement atmosphere with exposed brick walls and seating to accommodate 30 or more people at communal tables, deuces along the walls, and a sofa up front. There’s also a patio out back. During summer, be aware that the huge air conditioning units on the ceiling blow cold air directly onto certain seats, making it very cold to sit there. Outlets are only available along the walls, so there tend to be wires across the floor.
image1alt: Baby blue sign with the words "The Chipped Cup" painted on it.
image2alt: Latte art in a blue cup with a croissant next to it.
image3alt: Man with red hat leaning over his laptop at a seated bar area.
image4alt: Corner of The Chipped Cup with artistic wallpaper and eclectic picture frames.

name: Ground Central Coffee Company
address: 155 East 52nd Street, 3rd Ave, New York, NY 10022
about: Ground Coffee is merges the best of NYC: rock music, wall art murals, and artisan coffee. You'll find a library-style area in the back of the coffee shop with leather couches pushed against a wall of books.
miniblurb: Independent coffee shop with stacked bookshelves, artistic wall art, dark interior decor, and rock music.
insidertips: The room at the back is filled with comfy chairs and couches. Great for a few hours of work on a rainy day. Front area is great but rock music plays fairly loud, so don’t try to do a conference call. Wifi is fast.
image1alt: Interior of Ground Central: people sitting on black leather couches, working on laptops or reading. Bookcase behind them.
image2alt: Croissant and coffee in a black cup that reads "Ground Central"
image3alt: Front of Ground Central Coffee: stools next to coffee bar.
